<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-004-249 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 614 396</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Dec 1991 v16 n13 p150(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Multimedia: solutions anticipating a market. (overview to aspecial section on multimedia technologies)(State of the Art)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Donovan, John W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Multimedia computing, already being touted as the next revolutionin computing, may someday provide true virtual reality.andP;  In thepresent time, however, the humanization of information broughtabout by multimedia technology is already poised to launch aseries of 'mini-revolutions' in areas that include education andthe conduct of business on both the personal and professionallevels.andP;  It is also forecast that multimedia will replace thegraphical user interface (GUI) as the most popular human-computerinterface at the microcomputer level.andP;  The state of the art inmultimedia today is a merging of television with the computer.andO;Future developments will require intensive development in allareas of technology, including microprocessors, operating systemsand supporting software.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Future of ComputingOutlookImpact AnalysisMultimedia technologyHuman Factors.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>